White house urges north korea to shut down nuclear reactor
the white house today called for the dispatch of nuclear inspectors to supervise north korea to shut down its nuclear reactor , an appeal made after us president George w. bush and south Korean president Roh Moo - hyun talked by telephone .
White house national security council spokesman John Chandler said the two leaders " discussed recent developments in us - south Korean cooperation on the north Korean nuclear issue and expected IAEA inspectors to return to north korea soon to supervise the suspension and closure of the north Korean nuclear reactor . "
Chandler pointed out that the two presidents also welcomed the us - south korea free trade agreement signed yesterday and will work to ensure that the two parliaments ratify the agreement .
experts believe that the plutonium produced by Pyongyang in the past 20 years is enough to make 12 nuclear weapons .
after visiting Pyongyang last week , us special envoy to the six - party talks hill said he expected the Yongbyon nuclear reactor to be shut down in mid - july .
43 killed in heavy rain in western india
heavy winds and torrential rain hit western india over the weekend , seriously flooding some areas , and all domestic and foreign air routes in the western big city of Bombay were suspended .
rescue officials said today that a total of 43 people were killed .
from june to september every year , strong monsoon winds and heavy rain often cause flooding and even casualties in india , a country with a population of 1.1 billion .
half of the victims were swept away and drowned in the torrential rain , while the rest were electrocuted by collapsing houses or electric wires .
India &apos;s financial center , Mumbai , was also affected .
on the 29th and 32nd alone , the rainfall in Mumbai reached 243 millimeters .
Bombay chief executive Bazak said 13 people were killed in the city alone .
city officials urged 15 million people not to go out until the heavy rain subsided .
rain rested yesterday and much of Mumbai is still flooded today .
Indian flood kills nearly 500 in rainy season
according to officials and media reports , the death toll from heavy rains in the rainy season has climbed to 474 across india this year .
the " news trust of india " quoted government minister in charge of disaster relief and reconstruction Katan as revealing today that india 's provinces have entered the rainy season one after another in the past week , causing heavy casualties and economic losses in various places . at present , the death toll in maharashtra province , where Mumbai , india 's largest city , is located , has reached 358 .
the report pointed out that during his visit to Mumbai , Kadan made the above remarks to media reporters .
he said : at the same time , Maharashtra province , india 's largest cotton producing area , has a vast expanse of land . 27 towns and about 2,000 villages have been seriously flooded , and more than 10,000 victims have been relocated to safe shelters .
throughout india , the rainy season began one after another from south to north a week ago . residents in various provinces greeted the heavy rain with the mood of prolonged drought and rain . however , the rainy season was unexpectedly fierce . one rainy day , roads became rivers , houses in low - lying areas were completely out of water , and traffic was nearly paralyzed . so far , it is estimated that nearly 500 people have lost their lives as a result of floods .
Joe Covic abandons Nadal for final at Wimbledon
Spain 's red earth king Nadal abstained in the final four of the men 's singles match at Wimbledon against Serbia 's Jokovic , who was unable to play again due to injury .
Djokovic , who had called in guards to heal his back in the final 16 and the final eight , decided to drop out after suffering a blistering toe and asking for medical attention in the third set today .
fourth seed jokovic withdrew from the race , allowing the second seed Nadal , who had a three - to - six , six - to - one , and four - to pass the test .
in addition to the fact that Nadal lost his first set at the beginning of the match due to too slow a heat engine , the two sets and the three sets were overwhelmingly ahead .
satellite images show iran digging tunnels to protect nuclear equipment
Iran is digging a tunnel in a mountain near the Natanz uranium enrichment facility , possibly to protect nuclear equipment in the event of an air strike , a us think tank , the institute for science and international security , reported today .
the images were taken by Digital Global of the United States on June 11 and posted on the website of the Institute for Science and International Security .
the institute is based in washington , D.C. , and is a non-profit research group .
the images show that road construction is proceeding along the mountain just 2.4 kilometers south of the Natanz facility , which houses a uranium enrichment plant .
analysts Albright and Brennan pointed out in a report that the entrance and exit of the tunnel in the image " is not clear , but " one of the roads seems to lead to one tunnel facility and the other road may lead to the entrance and exit of the tunnel . "
they said : " such a tunnel facility dug into the mountains will play an excellent protective role in the air raid . "
Iran remains tough on un envoy 's nuclear talks
Deputy director - general of the united nations ' international atomic energy agency ( IAEA ) Heinonen today held talks with Iranian officials in Tehran to try again to resolve the deadlock over iran 's nuclear program .
however , Iranian president Ahmadinejad is still stubbornly resisting under increasing pressure from the united nations for further sanctions .
Ahmadinejad insisted iran would not halt uranium enrichment , but welcomed the latest talks .
he said : &quot; the trend of installing centrifuges can be slowed or accelerated . this is a problem of implementation . however , no one should expect us to give up our rights . we will not stop this trend . &quot;
he made the remarks after Heinonen arrived in Tehran .
the purpose of Hainonen 's visit is to draw up a set of plans to resolve " outstanding issues " arising from iran 's nuclear program .
the united nations has imposed two sets of sanctions on iran over Tehran 's failure to freeze uranium enrichment operations .
the " iran news agency " reported that Hainonen held talks with officials headed by Vadi , assistant chairman in charge of international affairs of iran 's supreme national security council .
Iran 's team also includes IAEA vice - chairman Saeidi and ambassador to the international atomic energy agency Sotanya .
the emergency period Palestinian Prime Minister Fayyad will form a new government . &quot;
the palestinian authority imposed a one - month state of emergency after Hamas militants seized the gaza strip . Prime minister Fayyad resigned temporarily today , but was immediately tasked with forming a new government . "
" Prime minister Fayyad submitted his resignation to president Abbas and the chairman accepted it . at the same time , he also asked him to form a new cabinet government to handle daily affairs , " agriculture and social affairs minister Habahi told afp .
Abbas 's confidant Ammer told afp that Fayyad submitted his resignation and Abbas ordered him to " carry out his current duties until he prepares to form a new government . "
the resignation of the well - respected economist Fayyad is only a procedural resignation and will not shake his position as prime minister .
Fayyad has been leading the palestinian emergency cabinet since the 17 th of last month and is responsible for implementing the state of emergency order announced by Abbas after Hamas violently seized gaza .
according to the basic law of the palestinian self - government , a state of emergency cannot last more than 30 days without the consent of the palestinian parliament , which is now paralysed .
the emergency government &apos;s authorization expires today .
WTO representative introduces bill to break deadlock in doha round talks
the world trade organization ( wto ) today proposed that the united states slash agricultural subsidies and developing countries slash tariffs on imports of industrial products to break the deadlock in the doha round of trade talks .
officials said that the new " draft model " requires the united states to reduce its annual agricultural subsidies from the currently allowed 19 billion us dollars to 16.2 billion us dollars , and developing countries to reduce import tariffs on industrial products to less than 23 percent .
the proposals are aimed at breaking the deadlock in the doha round negotiations over the past six years and bringing about a compromise agreement among 150 wto members .
WTO Secretary General Lamy called the proposals &quot; a fair and reasonable basis for reaching ambitious , balanced and development-oriented agreements . &quot;
Lamy said : &quot; Member States will not be completely satisfied with the contents of the proposal , but the issues that have caused differences are fewer than those that have achieved consensus . &quot;
he called for intensive negotiations in the coming weeks .
the strong earthquake affects the auto factory to reduce or stop production on the production day of spare parts
automakers such as toyota and Nissan said Tuesday they would cut back or even suspend domestic car production as a result of a severe earthquake that hit japan this week .
Japan was hit by a 6.8 magnitude earthquake the day before yesterday , forcing auto parts maker Ri Research Corp. to suspend operation of factories in northwestern Tokyo , which in turn affected car factory production .
Toyota , the world 's best-selling car maker , will suspend domestic car production from tonight to the 21st , a spokeswoman said .
Nissan spokesman Nakagawa said that from the day after tomorrow to the 23rd , two of Nissan 's three factories in japan will suspend some production operations and will reassess the situation over the weekend .
he said that the two factories have two production lines , one of which will be affected , but the company may increase its shift next month to make up for the backward production progress .
Suzuki said partial production would be suspended for three days from tomorrow , and japan 's Fuji heavy industry company , which makes Subaru cars , would also suspend production of small cars from tomorrow and assess the situation on the 21st .
Honda , on the other hand , said it may suspend production lines that depend in part on the supply of spare parts next week .
the quake killed at least 10 people , injured more than 1,000 , and toppled hundreds of houses , forcing factories in the disaster area to shut down .
Indonesia to Stop Selling British Brand Environmental Bags
Indonesia has canceled the sale of brand - name green bags in the united kingdom in view of the disorder caused by a rush to buy in Hong kong earlier this month , the agency said today .
&quot; in view of the events in Hong Kong , we canceled the listing of the environmentally friendly bags , &quot; said OnPedder , a person in charge of the famous OnPedder store in Indonesia Square , a high consumption area .
if the people fight violently for a bag of 140,000 rupees ( about nt $ 494 ) , then it will not have that value . "
thousands of Hong Kong people gathered outside the sales store on the 6th to rush to buy a limited number of environmentally friendly bags designed by British designer Anya Hindmark and printed with the words &quot; I am not a plastic bag . &quot; however , the store owner refused to open the door , causing the scene to get out of hand .
in an attempt to replace plastic bags , this environmentally friendly boutique suddenly became popular in london and new york , triggering a rush to buy it . the price on eBay , an auction site , has soared to several times the retail price .
OnPedder , the only one who won the right to sell in Indonesia , said it was not sure whether it would start selling in a few days .
countdown to hostage crisis : South korea holds direct talks with Taliban
the afghan Taliban kidnapped 23 south Korean hostages and set a sunset deadline for south korea to withdraw its troops from afghanistan or kill the hostages .
South Korean officials today held talks with the Taliban for the first time as time passed and the situation developed in a positive way .
but at the same time , the Taliban said another kidnapped german hostage was very weak and began to fall into a coma and lose consciousness .
the Taliban called on Germany and south korea to withdraw their troops from afghanistan and demanded that the hostages be exchanged for 33 guerrillas imprisoned by the afghan government .
Taliban spokesman Amadi told afp by telephone from an unknown location : " we have direct contact with south Korean representatives through tribal elders . "
Amadeus said : " we hope the talks will yield results . "
the Taliban have set a deadline for killing south Korean hostages in the evening ( 10.30 pm Taiwan time ) .
the guerrillas have extended the deadline twice .
maritime disputes difficult to gather consensus military talks between the two Koreas broke up unhappily
the three - day high - level military talks between the two Koreas broke up unhappily today due to different views on the demarcation of maritime boundaries .
at the talks held in the border city of Panmunjom today , entering the last day of the agenda , North Korea &apos;s chief representative , Lieutenant General Kim Jung Chol ( transliterated ) , said : &quot; we have come to the conclusion that these inconclusive talks are no longer needed . &quot;
flushed and visibly unhappy , Kim Jung - Chol criticized south korea for deliberately avoiding delimiting a new maritime boundary to replace the discussion on the original " northern limit line . "
he pointed out that the &quot; Northern Limit Line &quot; was not legal .
the &quot; Northern Limit Line &quot; in the Yellow Sea was drawn by the US military after the end of the Korean War in 1953 . however , it has become the focus of dispute between the two Koreas in recent years , and North Korea has even refused to acknowledge it .
North korea said south Korean warships illegally intruded into the waters , triggering tensions , an allegation south korea said was groundless .
clashes broke out in local waters in june 1999 , killing dozens of north Korean sailors .
in june 2002 , similar clashes broke out again , tragically killing six south Koreans .
US treasury secretary visits china to focus on environmental protection and exchange rate
US treasury secretary Paulson arrived in china yesterday for a visit . the united states is making every effort to persuade china to further carry out necessary economic reforms and environmental protection work , especially on the issue of the renminbi exchange rate , which has attracted much attention .
US diplomats said Paulson first went to Xining , capital of Qinghai , a major province in northwest china .
China is currently implementing a series of environmental protection projects near the largest saltwater lake in Qinghai province .
Paulson transferred to beijing today to discuss with chinese officials the process of promoting the " us - china strategic economic dialogue " launched last year and other topics .
the us - china strategic economic dialogue mainly discusses economic , environmental protection , and other topics . the most important issue is the RMB exchange rate . US congressmen believe that the renminbi 's value is excessively undervalued .
the us - china trade deficit is rapidly soaring and pressure is gradually rising in the united states . congressmen are prepared to take retaliatory action to confront their so - called unfair trade policy of china .
last week , the us senate finance committee overwhelmingly passed a bill requiring the treasury department to designate a list of countries whose currency exchange rate is " fundamentally misvalued , " opening the door to potential economic sanctions against beijing .
US congressmen said that the undervaluation of the renminbi made china 's goods sold to the united states very cheap and aggravated the us - china trade imbalance . last year , the us trade deficit with china reached $ 232.5 billion .
