US defense department reconsiders plans to reduce us troops in europe
due to the iraq war and changes in the world situation , the us defense department is reconsidering its plan to cut the number of us troops in europe by about half , a us defense department official said on the 23 rd .
the us media quoted a defense department official as saying that since the iraq war is still going on and us relations with russia and iran have deteriorated , the defense department leadership has questioned the feasibility of the plan to reduce the number of european troops stationed .
in 2002 , then defense secretary Donald Rumsfeld announced that the united states would reduce the number of troops stationed in europe from 113,000 to 71,000 by 2012 in order to build a new type of army that is small and capable .
at present , the total number of us troops stationed in europe has dropped to 100,000 .
however , in june this year , Craddock , commander of the us european command , submitted a report to current defense secretary gates , questioning the above - mentioned reduction plan .
the report said that while the us troops stationed in europe were reducing their strength , many troops were transferred to iraq and afghanistan in turn , leaving the us troops stationed in europe short of personnel and unable to carry out normal cooperation with its european allies .
the report recommends stopping the planned reduction of us troops in europe .
relevant us experts believe that the above phenomenon shows that the prolonged delay in the iraq war has disrupted the original adjustment plan of the us military .
